	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Expanded cocoa production required to meet growing demand</h1>

			
			<h4>
												27 December 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>While cocoa prices recently fell to a 2-year low, a ‘top ranked chocolate maker’ claimed in November 2011 that ‘world cocoa production needs to rise more than one-quarter to spare confectioners “significant challenges” in securing supplies.’ Juergen Steinemann, chief executive of industrial chocolate manufacturer Barry Callebaut, claimed that such a level of production expansion would be necessary in view of the growth in demand for chocolate of 2 to 3% per annum, largely resulting from expanding demand in newly emerging economies, particularly in Asia. In the year to the end of August 2011, the volume of chocolate sales by Barry Callebaut to the Asian market reportedly rose 10.4% (compared to a global increase of 7.2% for the company and a global industry-wide expansion of 3.1%).</p><p>Mr Steinemann argued that it was increasingly apparent that the company’s industrial customers would be in the Asia–Pacific region, which he described as ‘the next growth area’. However, the key to exploiting this emerging market was seen as securing supplies of cocoa from the principal producers in Africa. With this in mind, the company recently announced the launch of an initiative to support yields and quality improvements among West African cocoa producers.</p><p>This forms part of a wider range of private–public sector partnerships which have been launched to boost cocoa production in West Africa. In November, the launch of a US$5 million ‘experimental research station’ in Côte d’Ivoire was announced, seeking to bring together the research efforts of the National Centre of Agronomic Research (NCAR) and the private research efforts of Nestlé, both aimed at boosting cocoa production. Ivorian cocoa producer organisations are reassured by the presence of NCAR in the collaborative effort, with many growers concerned that ‘the commercial firm may be acting in its own interests’.</p><p>Comoé Marius, president of the Ivory Coast Consumers’ Organisation, expressed the hope that ‘Nestlé will not work for only its own profit but also for the cocoa producers of the Ivory Coast, and will help them to increase their income and improve their quality of life.’</p><p>November also saw the launch of a partnership between US multinational Cargill and Anader, the Côte d’Ivoire national rural development support agency, bringing 1.5 billion CFA francs (€2.3m) investment in training for producers and the distribution of 600,000 new cocoa plants. The emphasis of the public–private partnership will be on improving agricultural practices and post-harvest activities, ‘in order to improve yields and quality, improve good governance in cooperatives and raise producers’ incomes via the certification premium’.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
