<a href="http://www.agrimoney.com/news/world-needs-extra-1m-tonnes-of-cocoa-by-2020--3831.html" target="_self">http://www.agrimoney.com/news/world-needs-extra-1m-tonnes-of-cocoa-by-20...</a></p><p><i>SciDev.Net</i>, ‘Centre aims to revive cocoa fields’, 16 November 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://allafrica.com/stories/201111170430.html" target="_self">http://allafrica.com/stories/201111170430.html</a></p><p><i>CommodAfrica.com</i>, ‘Cargill prévoit d’acheter 50 000 T de cacao certifié ivoirien en 2011/12&nbsp;: La multinationale américaine renforce son partenariat avec l’Anader’, 14 November 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.commodafrica.com/fr/actualites/matieres_premieres/cargillcacaocotedivoire" target="_self">http://www.commodafrica.com/fr/actualites/matieres_premieres/cargillcaca...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Barry Callebaut provides an example of a European company exploiting rapidly growing demand in the Asia–Pacific region on the basis of raw materials supplied from Africa. The challenge for West African cocoa-producing countries is to use international concerns over future supplies to enable them to meet expanding demand in the Asia–Pacific region, by leveraging new relationships which progressively move the West African cocoa economy up the value chain, transforming the basis of its integration into the global cocoa/chocolate supply chain.</p><p>This provides one example of how the new global economic dynamic, created by the increasing role of emerging economies, could be used by African countries to transform the basis of their relationship into particular supply chains.</p><p>In addition, the concerns expressed by farmers’ leaders also highlight the importance of reviewing how cocoa supply chains operate, in order to ensure that any expansion of cocoa production in West Africa benefits producers and doesn’t simply result in price declines which leave them worse off overall.</p>
		</div>
		
